Quick code tutorial: Quick start and generate text Last Updated : 2025-11-08 You can prompt a model to generate text programmatically with the watsonx.ai API and SDKs. This tutorial demonstrates how to get ready to start coding with watsonx.ai and how to generate an answer to a question about the distance between Paris and Bangalore. Work with Python, Node.js, or Curl. You can complete this tutorial in less than 5 minutes. Detailed information Building prompts Supported models Prerequisite one-time tasks Before you start running code in quick start tutorials, you must gather your credentials and other information and set up your system. Step 1: Sign up for watsonx To sign up for a free trial, go to Try watsonx for free . Step 2: Gather your information To gather the information that you need to call watsonx.ai APIs, go to the Developer access area of the watsonx.ai home page and copy these values: Project ID or Space ID. Your sandbox project is created automatically. watsonx.ai URL for calling APIs. API key. If you don't have an API key, click Create API key . Step 3: Prepare your system Python Node.js Curl To prepare your system: Install the Python library: pip install ibm-watsonx-ai Copy to clipboard Create a file named example.py . To prepare your system: Install the Node.js library: npm install @ibm-cloud/watsonx-ai Copy to clipboard Create a file with the .env extension to set environment variables. Add the following code to the file and replace {apikey} with your API key. WATSONX_AI_AUTH_TYPE=iam
WATSONX_AI_APIKEY={apikey} Copy to clipboard Create a file named example.js . You need an IBM Cloud bearer token. Skip this task if you already have an IBM Cloud bearer token. See IBM Cloud docs: Generating IBM Cloud IAM tokens . To generate an IBM Cloud bearer token, make a request to the IAM Identity Services API with your API key after replacing {apikey} with your API key: curl -X POST \
-H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \
https://iam.cloud.ibm.com/identity/token \
-d "grant_type=urn:ibm:params:oauth:grant-type:apikey&apikey={apikey}" Copy to clipboard Generate text Python Node.js Curl To generate text, add the following code to the example.py file. Replace {watsonx_ai_url} , {apikey} , and {project_id} with your values. from ibm_watsonx_ai import APIClient from ibm_watsonx_ai import Credentials from ibm_watsonx_ai.foundation_models import ModelInference
credentials = Credentials(
   url = "{watsonx_ai_url}" ,
   api_key = "{apikey}" ,
)
client = APIClient(credentials)

   model = ModelInference(
model_id= "ibm/granite-13b-instruct-v2" ,
api_client=client,
project_id= "{project_id}" ,
params = { "max_new_tokens" : 100 }
)
prompt = 'How far is Paris from Bangalore?' print (model.generate(prompt)) print (model.generate_text(prompt)) Copy to clipboard To generate text, add the following code to the example.js file. Replace {watsonx_ai_url} and {project_id} with your values. const { WatsonXAI } = require( '@ibm-cloud/watsonx-ai' );

process.env.IBM_CREDENTIALS_FILE = './.env' ; // Your file with the apikey

const watsonxAIService = WatsonXAI.newInstance({
version: '2024-05-31' ,
serviceUrl: '{watsonx_ai_url}' ,

});

const params = {
input: 'How far is Paris from Bangalore?' ,
modelId: 'ibm/granite-13b-instruct-v2' ,
projectId: '{project_id}' ,
parameters: {
   max_new_tokens: 100,
},
};

try {
const textGeneration = watsonxAIService.generateText(params). then ((res) => {
   console.log({ response: res.result.results[ 0 ].generated_text });
});
} catch (err) {
console.warn(err);
} Copy to clipboard To generate text, run the following curl request. Replace {token} , {watsonx_ai_url} , and {project_id} with your values. curl -X POST \
-H "Authorization: Bearer {token}" \
-H "Content-Type: application/json" \
-H 'Accept: application/json' \ "{watsonx_ai_url}/ml/v1/text/generation?version=2024-05-31" \
--data-raw '{
   "input": "How far is Paris from Bangalore?",
   "model_id": "ibm/granite-13b-instruct-v2",
   "project_id": "{project_id}"
}' Copy to clipboard Next steps Try your request against another foundation model by changing the value of the model_id parameter. See List supported models . Try another quick start coding tutorial. Learn more Building prompts Python library Node.js library watsonx.ai REST API
